g.aria-label: So standing waves are essentially waves created by interference of 2 waves moving in opposite directions to each other (or) when the medium moves opposite to the direction of the wave itself.One essential feature of the standing wave is that while the wave itself oscillates with time,the peak amplitudes of the wave are always found at the same x coordinate.

While transverse waves on a string vary in their displacement perpendicular to the direction of wave motion, the sound waves traveling through the air in the pipe vary in terms of their pressure and displacement along the direction of wave motion.

Ah yes I remember! The wave propagates by alternately compressing and expanding air in segments of the pipe (Compressions and Rarefactions), which displaces the air slightly from its rest position and transfers energy to neighboring segments through the forces exerted by the alternating high and low air pressures.

Thats right! Equations resembling those for the wave on a string can be written for the change in pressure due to a right- or left-traveling wave in the pipe.So a standing pressure wave form is fixed in space but oscillates in time.

However , in the case of a transverse wave,we write it in terms of a displacement wave.Displacement nodes and antinodes are points that undergo minimum and maximum displacements respectively. In terms of pressure, they are actually the opposite.

So, in the absence of the metal plates, we consider discrete collections of air molecules which we can call as a gas parcel inside the tube. Owing to the displacement component, they will oscillate back and forth about their mean position and also contract and expand simultaneously due to compression and rarefaction. As they get compressed,they heat up and they cool down as they expand.
Now when we place the metal plates in the tube what do you think might happen?
